1
00:00:09,166 --> 00:00:10,625
[MAGE]
Memory.

2
00:00:10,708 --> 00:00:12,708
♪

3
00:00:15,041 --> 00:00:17,500
The garden where
the tuberoses still bloom.

4
00:00:17,583 --> 00:00:19,875
[breeze blowing]

5
00:00:21,250 --> 00:00:22,500
[gasp]

6
00:00:24,750 --> 00:00:26,750
[breeze blowing]

7
00:00:27,750 --> 00:00:29,791
That’s where I’m waiting.

8
00:00:33,250 --> 00:00:34,666
The mystery of time.

9
00:00:35,666 --> 00:00:37,625
Will it never be solved?

10
00:00:37,708 --> 00:00:39,750
♪

11
00:00:39,833 --> 00:00:41,375
I am waiting for the time,

12
00:00:42,375 --> 00:00:44,750
when you turn back,

13
00:00:44,833 --> 00:00:46,833
and give me the real answer.

14
00:02:07,416 --> 00:02:09,916
♪

15
00:02:10,916 --> 00:02:13,166
[door clanks]

16
00:02:13,250 --> 00:02:14,750
[BOTH panting]

17
00:02:20,250 --> 00:02:21,500
-[YURI] Wait!
-[gasp]

18
00:02:21,583 --> 00:02:23,916
[YURI] If Mage really
is behind this door,

19
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,458
and it turns out that you can

20
00:02:25,541 --> 00:02:27,041
change the world
with a time ride,

21
00:02:28,666 --> 00:02:30,166
then...

22
00:02:31,166 --> 00:02:32,583
♪

23
00:02:36,750 --> 00:02:38,000
[DERRIDA]
Yuri...

24
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,416
I get it. I know.

25
00:02:42,541 --> 00:02:44,541
I know how much you’ve suffered,

26
00:02:44,625 --> 00:02:46,500
just to get here.

27
00:02:46,583 --> 00:02:50,083
I know how sad and painful
it must have been, but...

28
00:02:50,166 --> 00:02:52,041
[YURI crying]

29
00:02:52,125 --> 00:02:54,166
If you change the past,

30
00:02:54,250 --> 00:02:55,916
then all of my memories...

31
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:56,791
[YURI shudders]

32
00:02:56,875 --> 00:02:58,291
they’ll disappear.

33
00:02:58,375 --> 00:02:59,291
[YURI sobs]

34
00:02:59,375 --> 00:03:01,291
I don’t wanna forget!

35
00:03:01,375 --> 00:03:02,708
Hey...

36
00:03:02,791 --> 00:03:04,791
[YURI] I’ve traveled
all this way with you.

37
00:03:04,875 --> 00:03:07,083
-We’ve been through so much.
-[DERRIDA sighs]

38
00:03:07,166 --> 00:03:08,708
And...

39
00:03:08,791 --> 00:03:10,916
I don’t wanna lose
my memories of this.

40
00:03:11,916 --> 00:03:14,416
None of them,
no matter how small!

41
00:03:15,708 --> 00:03:17,458
Because it’s you, Derrida.

42
00:03:17,541 --> 00:03:18,791
[gasp]

43
00:03:19,958 --> 00:03:22,250
[YURI]
But, I understand.

44
00:03:22,333 --> 00:03:24,458
There’s no future
left for this world.

45
00:03:24,541 --> 00:03:27,791
If I have to give up
my precious memories,

46
00:03:27,875 --> 00:03:31,208
at least it will be so that
everyone can have a future.

47
00:03:32,208 --> 00:03:34,666
That’s what you were
going to say, right?

48
00:03:35,666 --> 00:03:36,625
Yes.

49
00:03:36,708 --> 00:03:38,083
[sniff, chuckle]

50
00:03:39,083 --> 00:03:42,083
Figured, so I thought
I’d beat you to it this time.

51
00:03:43,708 --> 00:03:45,458
Well, let’s go, then!

52
00:03:46,708 --> 00:03:47,791
Yeah.

53
00:03:47,875 --> 00:03:49,250
[gunfire]

54
00:03:49,333 --> 00:03:51,208
[groaning, yelling]

55
00:03:51,291 --> 00:03:52,083
[smashing]

56
00:03:52,166 --> 00:03:53,083
[VIDAUX yelling]

57
00:03:53,166 --> 00:03:54,000
[smashing]

58
00:03:55,458 --> 00:03:56,333
[crash]

59
00:03:57,583 --> 00:03:59,125
-[cases rattling]
-[gunfire]

60
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:01,208
♪

61
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:05,791
-[bang]
-[grunt, groaning]

62
00:04:05,875 --> 00:04:08,375
[crackling]

63
00:04:08,458 --> 00:04:09,375
[groaning]

64
00:04:11,416 --> 00:04:12,708
-[MAYUKA] Papa!
-[gasp]

65
00:04:12,791 --> 00:04:13,916
[panting]

66
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:15,500
[groaning]

67
00:04:15,583 --> 00:04:17,416
Yah!

68
00:04:17,500 --> 00:04:19,416
-[MAYUKA panting]
-Mayuka! Why’re you here?

69
00:04:19,500 --> 00:04:21,250
‘Cause I wanted to be with you!

70
00:04:21,333 --> 00:04:22,750
[VIDAUX sighs]

71
00:04:22,833 --> 00:04:24,041
[gasp]
Stubborn girl.

72
00:04:25,041 --> 00:04:26,208
[whimper]

73
00:04:28,083 --> 00:04:29,583
-[gun clicks]
-[VIDAUX] I’ll protect you,

74
00:04:29,666 --> 00:04:31,125
no matter what!

75
00:04:31,208 --> 00:04:32,750
[gunfire]

76
00:04:32,833 --> 00:04:34,000
[blast]

77
00:04:36,416 --> 00:04:38,958
-Okay, hold on!
-Mm!

78
00:04:43,166 --> 00:04:45,250
[door clicks, whirs]

79
00:04:49,041 --> 00:04:50,541
[door clangs]

80
00:04:51,541 --> 00:04:52,833
[heavy sigh]

81
00:04:52,916 --> 00:04:54,166
[DERRIDA gasps]

82
00:04:56,875 --> 00:05:00,333
♪

83
00:05:02,708 --> 00:05:04,541
♪ Time flows by ♪

84
00:05:06,416 --> 00:05:08,416
♪ A second, minutes ♪

85
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:11,750
♪ An hour, for eternity ♪

86
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:18,666
This room...
How could I forget?

87
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:29,041
[DERRIDA]
It’s a room full of memories.

88
00:05:31,958 --> 00:05:34,291
-[piano playing]
-Huh?

89
00:05:40,541 --> 00:05:42,083
Memories...

90
00:05:43,083 --> 00:05:44,458
[DERRIDA]
Vividness of memory

91
00:05:44,541 --> 00:05:46,791
enhances the time
ride’s precision.

92
00:05:46,875 --> 00:05:50,250
She recreated this room that’s
full of so many memories,

93
00:05:50,333 --> 00:05:53,000
to try to extend
the distance of her jumps.

94
00:05:53,083 --> 00:05:55,541
If that’s true, then...

95
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,750
[YURI]
She must be here!

96
00:05:59,833 --> 00:06:01,916
-Where are you, Mage?
-It’s us!

97
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:03,458
[footsteps]

98
00:06:03,541 --> 00:06:04,791
[slams door]

99
00:06:06,625 --> 00:06:08,625
♪

100
00:06:12,125 --> 00:06:15,041
♪ There is a colorful path ♪

101
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:17,416
♪ Which has happened ♪

102
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:18,791
[YURI]
Mage!

103
00:06:20,083 --> 00:06:23,041
♪ Vividness through
all the motions ♪

104
00:06:23,125 --> 00:06:24,083
This is...

105
00:06:24,166 --> 00:06:27,875
♪ Colors accentuate identity ♪

106
00:06:28,875 --> 00:06:30,041
♪ Time... ♪

107
00:06:30,125 --> 00:06:31,375
[DERRIDA]
Time ride hardware?

108
00:06:34,750 --> 00:06:35,583
[YURI] Derrida!

109
00:06:38,541 --> 00:06:40,583
“To Mage Bilstein.

110
00:06:40,666 --> 00:06:42,375
Be sure to watch this.”

111
00:06:42,458 --> 00:06:44,666
A letter?
Who do you think put it there?

112
00:06:45,666 --> 00:06:47,291
[click, static noise]

113
00:06:47,375 --> 00:06:49,375
-What, Mage?!
-[DERRIDA gasps]

114
00:06:50,375 --> 00:06:53,041
Hi, Mage.
This is your past self.

115
00:06:53,125 --> 00:06:55,375
I’m sure you’re
feeling disoriented.

116
00:06:55,458 --> 00:06:57,041
I’m confused myself, honestly.

117
00:06:57,125 --> 00:06:59,041
I’m leaving this video record,

118
00:06:59,125 --> 00:07:01,708
so that I don’t forget
what’s important.

119
00:07:01,791 --> 00:07:03,541
Did she write
this note herself?

120
00:07:03,625 --> 00:07:06,125
Did she think she’d
forget to watch the video?

121
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:10,083
Because she knows time
rides erase memories.

122
00:07:10,166 --> 00:07:11,416
That's why.

123
00:07:11,500 --> 00:07:14,666
Don’t forget, what
your ultimate goal is.

124
00:07:14,750 --> 00:07:16,291
Find Derrida Yvain,

125
00:07:16,375 --> 00:07:18,416
-and send him into the past.
-[gasp]

126
00:07:19,416 --> 00:07:21,333
[MAGE]
Even if I can’t do it,

127
00:07:21,416 --> 00:07:22,958
Derrida can.

128
00:07:23,041 --> 00:07:25,875
He can return this world to
the place where it belongs.

129
00:07:25,958 --> 00:07:29,125
It feels so strange to
see my face like this,

130
00:07:29,208 --> 00:07:31,375
reflected on this monitor.

131
00:07:31,458 --> 00:07:35,041
I can’t remember anything
from before I was 14.

132
00:07:35,125 --> 00:07:36,166
I...

133
00:07:36,250 --> 00:07:38,500
managed to perfect
the time ride.

134
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:42,208
And so I’m losing
memories in exchange.

135
00:07:43,208 --> 00:07:46,208
But there’s one thing
that I do remember.

136
00:07:47,208 --> 00:07:48,541
Derrida.

137
00:07:48,625 --> 00:07:51,041
I need to save Derrida.

138
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:54,125
I must.
[gasp]

139
00:07:54,208 --> 00:07:56,291
-Please, Ange!
-Wait, Ange?!

140
00:07:56,375 --> 00:07:57,166
Who?

141
00:07:57,250 --> 00:07:58,791
Help me.

142
00:07:58,875 --> 00:08:00,666
Please save Derrida.

143
00:08:01,666 --> 00:08:02,666
[DERRIDA gasps]

144
00:08:04,541 --> 00:08:05,875
[inaudible]

145
00:08:05,958 --> 00:08:08,916
♪

146
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,791
[YURI] What does this mean?
What was she planning?

147
00:08:11,875 --> 00:08:12,875
[DERRIDA]
So, that’s it.

148
00:08:13,875 --> 00:08:16,208
-What is?
-I see now.

149
00:08:16,291 --> 00:08:17,875
Why didn’t I realize it?

150
00:08:17,958 --> 00:08:20,291
Was it Mage who was
making you time ride?

151
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:23,875
But why? And how?

152
00:08:23,958 --> 00:08:25,250
[DERRIDA]
According to the Trout Theory,

153
00:08:25,333 --> 00:08:27,125
traveling through time requires

154
00:08:27,208 --> 00:08:29,541
significant hardware
to support it.

155
00:08:29,625 --> 00:08:31,416
But, something happened

156
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:33,791
after I woke from
my 10-year sleep.

157
00:08:33,875 --> 00:08:36,208
I found myself repeatedly
thrust into the past

158
00:08:36,291 --> 00:08:39,208
without the assistance of
any equipment whatsoever.

159
00:08:40,208 --> 00:08:41,708
I thought,

160
00:08:41,791 --> 00:08:44,833
maybe what I was
experiencing was paranormal.

161
00:08:44,916 --> 00:08:46,708
But of course,
that couldn’t be the case.

162
00:08:47,708 --> 00:08:49,500
The hardware was here.

163
00:08:49,583 --> 00:08:53,125
And the time rides were
fed by vivid memories.

164
00:08:54,125 --> 00:08:56,500
Mage created a room
of memories here,

165
00:08:56,583 --> 00:08:59,625
trying to inspire powerful,
vivid recollections.

166
00:09:00,625 --> 00:09:03,125
[YURI] But, Mage couldn’t
travel back to 10 years ago?

167
00:09:04,458 --> 00:09:07,041
[DERRIDA] 10 years was too
far in the past for her.

168
00:09:07,125 --> 00:09:10,041
[YURI]
So, why did she pick you?

169
00:09:11,041 --> 00:09:13,166
For a man who’s been
asleep for 10 years,

170
00:09:13,250 --> 00:09:15,250
it was just like yesterday.

171
00:09:15,333 --> 00:09:16,833
I could go back.

172
00:09:16,916 --> 00:09:19,666
But, how’d she manage to
reach you from so far away?

173
00:09:19,750 --> 00:09:20,541
[DERRIDA gasps]

174
00:09:20,625 --> 00:09:21,458
[chain rattles]

175
00:09:22,458 --> 00:09:23,250
[click]

176
00:09:23,333 --> 00:09:25,375
[disassembling]

177
00:09:25,458 --> 00:09:26,333
[gasps]

178
00:09:27,708 --> 00:09:29,666
♪

179
00:09:29,750 --> 00:09:30,708
It was this!

180
00:09:35,041 --> 00:09:36,625
I didn’t even realize.

181
00:09:36,708 --> 00:09:38,333
But I...

182
00:09:38,416 --> 00:09:41,041
[YURI] Derrida! Do you think
something’s happened to Mage?

183
00:09:41,125 --> 00:09:42,666
[DERRIDA]
Well...

184
00:09:42,750 --> 00:09:44,625
I don’t know how many times
I’ve used this time ride.

185
00:09:44,708 --> 00:09:46,541
And in order to time ride,

186
00:09:46,625 --> 00:09:48,916
you need memories that
can be used as fuel.

187
00:09:49,916 --> 00:09:52,750
[DERRIDA] I wondered why
I wasn’t losing any memories.

188
00:09:52,833 --> 00:09:54,625
I thought maybe I just
couldn’t comprehend

189
00:09:54,708 --> 00:09:56,708
what I’d lost once it was gone.

190
00:09:58,458 --> 00:10:00,500
But now,
I see that was wrong.

191
00:10:01,500 --> 00:10:03,750
The fuel that I was using up

192
00:10:03,833 --> 00:10:05,458
was Mage’s memory.

193
00:10:06,458 --> 00:10:09,458
You mean she was sacrificing
her own memories?

194
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:12,625
Mage...

195
00:10:12,708 --> 00:10:14,166
Mage.

196
00:10:14,250 --> 00:10:16,000
Wake up, please!

197
00:10:17,708 --> 00:10:18,833
-[wince]
-[BOTH] She moved?!

198
00:10:18,916 --> 00:10:19,916
Who...

199
00:10:21,291 --> 00:10:23,250
[YURI]
It’s me! It’s Yuri!

200
00:10:23,333 --> 00:10:25,291
-Yuri?
-[DERRIDA] Mage.

201
00:10:25,375 --> 00:10:27,041
Hey, it’s me, Derrida!

202
00:10:27,125 --> 00:10:28,791
Derrida?

203
00:10:28,875 --> 00:10:31,875
That’s right!
I finally found you, Mage!

204
00:10:32,875 --> 00:10:34,625
Yeah.

205
00:10:34,708 --> 00:10:36,583
You made it in time, good.

206
00:10:37,750 --> 00:10:39,666
Don’t just
stand there, Derrida.

207
00:10:39,750 --> 00:10:42,458
-Quickly, come inside.
-Inside?

208
00:10:42,541 --> 00:10:44,458
And you too, Yuri. Hurry up.

209
00:10:44,541 --> 00:10:46,750
You’re going to
get covered in snow.

210
00:10:46,833 --> 00:10:49,458
This is that day.

211
00:10:49,541 --> 00:10:52,083
Her eighth birthday.
That’s what she’s seeing now.

212
00:10:52,166 --> 00:10:54,291
-[SCHMIDT] Derrida Yvain!
-[BOTH gasp]

213
00:10:56,458 --> 00:10:58,125
[SCHMIDT]
This is your final warning.

214
00:10:58,208 --> 00:11:00,708
The countdown has begun.

215
00:11:00,791 --> 00:11:03,166
The enemy is poised to
begin obliteration bombing.

216
00:11:03,250 --> 00:11:06,333
Soon, most of our country,
including this place,

217
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:08,041
-will become an inferno.
-[grunts]

218
00:11:08,125 --> 00:11:09,375
But,

219
00:11:09,458 --> 00:11:11,750
I happen to have some
information on areas

220
00:11:11,833 --> 00:11:14,916
the missile fallout won’t be
able to reach. So, let’s talk.

221
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:18,041
If you surrender now
and hand over your data,

222
00:11:18,125 --> 00:11:19,500
I will take you someplace safe.

223
00:11:19,583 --> 00:11:22,083
I’ll guarantee your
friends’ lives, too.

224
00:11:22,166 --> 00:11:24,000
Or are you still
under the delusion

225
00:11:24,083 --> 00:11:25,625
that you alone can
save the world?

226
00:11:25,708 --> 00:11:27,500
Don’t make me laugh!

227
00:11:27,583 --> 00:11:29,583
Who do you think you are? God?

228
00:11:29,666 --> 00:11:31,333
Come on out.

229
00:11:31,416 --> 00:11:33,833
Then we can have a toast,
you and I.

230
00:11:33,916 --> 00:11:35,250
To the end of the world!

231
00:11:36,250 --> 00:11:37,875
Damn you.

232
00:11:37,958 --> 00:11:39,500
-[MAGE] Derrida.
-[gasp]

233
00:11:39,583 --> 00:11:41,291
Derrida, please tell me.

234
00:11:41,375 --> 00:11:43,791
Why won’t you help my
dad with his research?

235
00:11:43,875 --> 00:11:46,208
[gasp]
Mage, I...

236
00:11:46,291 --> 00:11:48,416
-[air rushing]
-Derrida.

237
00:11:54,250 --> 00:11:56,500
-[DERRIDA] That’s it.
-[YURI] Huh?

238
00:11:57,750 --> 00:11:59,416
[DERRIDA]
That time.

239
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:00,833
That place.

240
00:12:01,833 --> 00:12:04,125
The place I should have
gone from the start!

241
00:12:09,083 --> 00:12:10,541
[DERRIDA]
I’m going home.

242
00:12:10,625 --> 00:12:13,125
To the place and the time

243
00:12:13,208 --> 00:12:15,625
that saw this disaster
set into motion.

244
00:12:15,708 --> 00:12:18,083
[SCHMIDT]
What’s the hold up, Yvain?

245
00:12:18,166 --> 00:12:20,125
You’re out of time!

246
00:12:20,208 --> 00:12:22,041
[DERRIDA]
If I don’t go,

247
00:12:22,125 --> 00:12:24,666
she’ll just be waiting in
here like this forever.

248
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:26,833
♪

249
00:12:26,916 --> 00:12:29,166
That means a time ride?

250
00:12:29,250 --> 00:12:30,958
Yeah.

251
00:12:31,041 --> 00:12:33,416
I understand now that there’s
something I need to say to her.

252
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:36,833
Once you do, what will happen?

253
00:12:36,916 --> 00:12:39,416
[DERRIDA]
I don’t know, but...

254
00:12:39,500 --> 00:12:42,583
everything’s pointing
to that time and place.

255
00:12:42,666 --> 00:12:44,458
I have to go.

256
00:12:44,541 --> 00:12:46,291
It’s like I said to Donna.

257
00:12:46,375 --> 00:12:47,875
We should fulfill
our obligations

258
00:12:47,958 --> 00:12:50,041
with no fear of failure.

259
00:12:50,125 --> 00:12:53,333
We have no hope of
a future otherwise. Yes.

260
00:12:53,416 --> 00:12:56,375
This will likely be
my final time ride.

261
00:12:56,458 --> 00:12:58,375
It’s dangerous!

262
00:12:58,458 --> 00:13:00,125
But I still have to do it.

263
00:13:01,125 --> 00:13:04,708
At this rate, everything will
be destroyed. Understand?

264
00:13:04,791 --> 00:13:06,625
Me, you, Mage.

265
00:13:06,708 --> 00:13:08,458
Vidaux and Mayuka, too.

266
00:13:09,666 --> 00:13:12,416
Everything and everyone
will be lost!

267
00:13:13,416 --> 00:13:15,208
Mage has been waiting
all this time.

268
00:13:16,208 --> 00:13:17,333
For me.

269
00:13:17,416 --> 00:13:19,083
To finally give
her my real answer.

270
00:13:20,916 --> 00:13:22,041
Hmm.

271
00:13:23,666 --> 00:13:25,583
[machinery powering up]

272
00:13:28,375 --> 00:13:30,333
[click, whir]

273
00:13:31,333 --> 00:13:34,250
[singing]
♪ There is a colorful path ♪

274
00:13:34,333 --> 00:13:38,000
♪ Which has happened ♪

275
00:13:38,083 --> 00:13:39,458
[wind blowing]

276
00:13:39,541 --> 00:13:41,000
♪ Vividness through... ♪

277
00:13:41,083 --> 00:13:43,250
Thank you.

278
00:13:43,333 --> 00:13:46,291
-[young and old YURI sing]
-[DERRIDA] Mage...

279
00:13:47,291 --> 00:13:49,750
This will be my last time ride.

280
00:13:49,833 --> 00:13:52,291
[YURI]
♪ Time goes by ♪

281
00:13:52,375 --> 00:13:53,500
[wind blowing]

282
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:55,333
[gasp] Hold on!

283
00:13:55,416 --> 00:13:56,583
-Derrida!
-Huh?

284
00:13:59,541 --> 00:14:00,500
I’m off.

285
00:14:00,583 --> 00:14:03,000
[crying]

286
00:14:03,083 --> 00:14:04,875
I’m not going to forget.

287
00:14:04,958 --> 00:14:06,458
[wind blowing]

288
00:14:08,916 --> 00:14:10,458
I won’t forget!

289
00:14:10,541 --> 00:14:12,583
[clock ticking slower]

290
00:14:17,458 --> 00:14:20,375
[energy whining, blasting]

291
00:14:23,083 --> 00:14:24,458
[ANGE]
You’re right.

292
00:14:24,541 --> 00:14:27,208
This really will be
the last time ride, Derrida.

293
00:14:27,291 --> 00:14:29,625
Do you know what you’re going
to do when you get there?

294
00:14:29,708 --> 00:14:31,708
It’s not about actions.

295
00:14:31,791 --> 00:14:33,000
It’s about what I’ll pursue.

296
00:14:33,083 --> 00:14:35,041
It’s about what I’ll hope for!

297
00:14:35,125 --> 00:14:36,791
-[wind blowing]
-[energy whining]

298
00:14:36,875 --> 00:14:38,500
[blast]

299
00:14:38,583 --> 00:14:41,750
[clock ticking faster, stops]

300
00:14:43,416 --> 00:14:46,416
♪

301
00:14:48,916 --> 00:14:50,208
[YOUNG MAGE]
This way! When it warms up,

302
00:14:50,291 --> 00:14:51,791
I wanna plant them right here!

303
00:14:54,125 --> 00:14:56,500
That sounds perfect.
I can’t wait.

304
00:14:56,583 --> 00:14:57,791
-[YOUNG MAGE] Hey, Derrida...
-Huh?

305
00:15:00,916 --> 00:15:02,166
Why...

306
00:15:02,250 --> 00:15:05,250
won’t you help my dad
with his research?

307
00:15:06,666 --> 00:15:08,375
With the time ride?

308
00:15:08,458 --> 00:15:11,500
Humans jumping through time
like that is just a fantasy.

309
00:15:11,583 --> 00:15:13,208
It’s not possible.

310
00:15:14,708 --> 00:15:17,291
[YOUNG MAGE] What is the key to
traveling through time?

311
00:15:17,375 --> 00:15:19,916
To memories that
can’t be erased.

312
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
To special times and places.

313
00:15:22,083 --> 00:15:23,541
Why do humans

314
00:15:23,625 --> 00:15:25,916
long to return to moments

315
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,708
they’ve randomly
designated as special?

316
00:15:28,791 --> 00:15:30,291
Wait, Mage?

317
00:15:31,291 --> 00:15:32,875
[chuckle]
You’re amazing.

318
00:15:32,958 --> 00:15:35,750
Not really. I’m quoting
your thesis, that’s all.

319
00:15:35,833 --> 00:15:38,875
Dad completely believes in
the theory that you proposed,

320
00:15:38,958 --> 00:15:40,291
and so do I.

321
00:15:40,375 --> 00:15:42,958
Mage, listen.

322
00:15:43,041 --> 00:15:45,083
It’s just...
[sighs]

323
00:15:48,500 --> 00:15:49,666
[sigh]

324
00:15:50,666 --> 00:15:52,458
Sorry.

325
00:15:52,541 --> 00:15:54,000
I have to apologize to you.

326
00:15:54,083 --> 00:15:55,583
Uh?

327
00:15:55,666 --> 00:15:56,833
[DERRIDA]
For acting in bad faith

328
00:15:56,916 --> 00:15:58,291
with you and your father

329
00:15:58,375 --> 00:16:00,708
when you tried to forward
my Trout Theory research.

330
00:16:02,041 --> 00:16:03,541
Do you mean that--

331
00:16:05,375 --> 00:16:08,166
[DERRIDA] If this is science
that will make people happy,

332
00:16:08,250 --> 00:16:10,958
if it’s something that will
give everyone a future...

333
00:16:12,083 --> 00:16:14,166
then I wanna
have the courage,

334
00:16:14,250 --> 00:16:16,166
and the determination
to pursue it.

335
00:16:16,250 --> 00:16:17,500
Then you’ll help?

336
00:16:17,583 --> 00:16:20,000
Yes. I promise you.

337
00:16:21,041 --> 00:16:23,333
I’ll help you and Nathan
with this research.

338
00:16:23,416 --> 00:16:25,083
[wind blowing]

339
00:16:25,166 --> 00:16:27,666
[DERRIDA]
Yes. This is for the best.

340
00:16:27,750 --> 00:16:30,750
♪

341
00:16:34,458 --> 00:16:36,791
[wind blowing]

342
00:16:36,875 --> 00:16:39,375
[energy humming, whining]

343
00:16:41,291 --> 00:16:42,375
[MAGE]
Dad!

344
00:16:43,375 --> 00:16:45,458
Derrida wanted me
to give this to you!

345
00:16:46,458 --> 00:16:47,291
[gasp]

346
00:16:50,750 --> 00:16:53,583
[DERRIDA] Originally,
Mage tried to run an experiment

347
00:16:53,666 --> 00:16:55,625
that night by
herself and collapsed.

348
00:16:56,625 --> 00:16:58,333
-Then, the next day,
-[inaudible talking]

349
00:16:58,416 --> 00:17:00,250
Nathan took Mage
to the hospital.

350
00:17:01,250 --> 00:17:03,250
[NATHAN]
Mage was doing an experiment.

351
00:17:03,333 --> 00:17:05,166
She’s unconscious.

352
00:17:06,250 --> 00:17:07,833
[beeping]

353
00:17:09,125 --> 00:17:10,666
[answers phone]

354
00:17:10,750 --> 00:17:11,916
[CASSIEL, distorted] I’m
calling to give you a warning.

355
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,083
Who’s this? What warning?

356
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:15,916
[CASSIEL] It’s up to you
whether to believe it or not,

357
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:17,625
but it’s extremely important.

358
00:17:17,708 --> 00:17:19,166
Your life may hang
in the balance.

359
00:17:21,166 --> 00:17:23,958
[NATHAN]
Mm. What did you say? Andrei?

360
00:17:24,041 --> 00:17:26,458
Hold on. Do you have proof?

361
00:17:26,541 --> 00:17:28,000
[CASSIEL]
I’m sending encrypted data

362
00:17:28,083 --> 00:17:29,666
directly to your console.

363
00:17:29,750 --> 00:17:31,208
[beeping]

364
00:17:31,291 --> 00:17:32,333
[NATHAN]
This is...

365
00:17:32,416 --> 00:17:34,833
I see. You’re right.

366
00:17:34,916 --> 00:17:38,000
We actually knew about the bug
and have already taken steps.

367
00:17:38,083 --> 00:17:40,333
I have the patch
file right here.

368
00:17:40,416 --> 00:17:43,041
If I act now,
I can probably stop their plan.

369
00:17:44,375 --> 00:17:46,583
I don’t know who you are,
but thank you.

370
00:17:46,666 --> 00:17:48,291
If I hadn’t
gotten your call,

371
00:17:48,375 --> 00:17:50,291
something awful
might have happened.

372
00:17:50,375 --> 00:17:52,625
[DERRIDA] Everything’s
playing out differently?

373
00:17:52,708 --> 00:17:53,958
[wind blowing]

374
00:17:54,041 --> 00:17:55,041
From...

375
00:17:56,041 --> 00:17:57,625
[gasp]

376
00:17:57,708 --> 00:18:00,250
[DERRIDA]
just those few words?

377
00:18:01,250 --> 00:18:03,375
[REPORTER] The exposure by
internal whistle-blowers

378
00:18:03,458 --> 00:18:05,416
of the massive graft
scandal at Rebuild

379
00:18:05,500 --> 00:18:08,125
has resulted in the arrest
of numerous executives

380
00:18:08,208 --> 00:18:09,958
from the company’s
upper echelon.

381
00:18:10,041 --> 00:18:12,958
The ramifications of these
arrests have already started

382
00:18:13,041 --> 00:18:15,250
to show themselves in
neighboring countries,

383
00:18:15,333 --> 00:18:17,625
as government officials
responsible for purchasing

384
00:18:17,708 --> 00:18:20,791
the combat DZs from
Rebuild have been arrested.

385
00:18:20,875 --> 00:18:22,916
And over 10,000 combat DZs,

386
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:24,833
intentionally programmed
to go berserk,

387
00:18:24,916 --> 00:18:26,666
have been confiscated.

388
00:18:26,750 --> 00:18:28,958
Daddy, what’re
they talking about?

389
00:18:29,041 --> 00:18:30,625
[DAD] It sounds like
the people that were trying

390
00:18:30,708 --> 00:18:33,041
to start a war have been
put in jail, sweetheart.

391
00:18:33,125 --> 00:18:34,166
[giggle]

392
00:18:34,250 --> 00:18:36,500
[YURI]
Oh, okay! That’s good!

393
00:18:38,208 --> 00:18:40,916
[wind blowing]

394
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:42,500
[DERRIDA]
Ange!

395
00:18:42,583 --> 00:18:44,833
I heard Mage asking you to
help her on that recording.

396
00:18:44,916 --> 00:18:46,750
Who are you?

397
00:18:46,833 --> 00:18:48,208
10 years ago, you died.

398
00:18:48,291 --> 00:18:50,583
Lost to the flames
with Nathan.

399
00:18:50,666 --> 00:18:53,375
Except Mage overwrote
that reality.

400
00:18:53,458 --> 00:18:54,416
Are you serious?

401
00:18:54,500 --> 00:18:55,916
As for me,

402
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:57,916
I never really existed at all.

403
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:01,416
The Mage in the world
where you didn’t die...

404
00:19:01,500 --> 00:19:05,291
♪

405
00:19:06,875 --> 00:19:08,583
[gasp]

406
00:19:08,666 --> 00:19:10,291
[ANGE]
Derrida,

407
00:19:10,375 --> 00:19:13,208
do you think the Trout Theory
is something that you created?

408
00:19:13,291 --> 00:19:14,583
[DERRIDA]
Huh?

409
00:19:14,666 --> 00:19:16,875
[ANGE] You merely awoke
it from its slumber.

410
00:19:16,958 --> 00:19:19,583
There is no single
past or future.

411
00:19:19,666 --> 00:19:21,083
It’s like a flowing river,

412
00:19:21,166 --> 00:19:24,083
breaking off into
many directions.

413
00:19:24,166 --> 00:19:26,875
Which branch do you follow?
What end will you reach?

414
00:19:26,958 --> 00:19:30,000
The secret of the Trout Theory
is that by wishing hard enough,

415
00:19:30,083 --> 00:19:31,583
humans can choose.

416
00:19:31,666 --> 00:19:32,500
[wind blowing]

417
00:19:33,708 --> 00:19:35,333
Mage wished
powerfully for a world

418
00:19:35,416 --> 00:19:37,666
in which you and Nathan
didn’t die,

419
00:19:37,750 --> 00:19:40,750
and she just barely managed
to save you, at least.

420
00:19:42,541 --> 00:19:45,625
And then, she entrusted
everything to you.

421
00:19:46,625 --> 00:19:48,416
[DERRIDA]
Mage... saved me?

422
00:19:48,500 --> 00:19:50,500
[ANGE]
That’s right. She saved you,

423
00:19:50,583 --> 00:19:52,500
and then you saved the world.

424
00:19:52,583 --> 00:19:55,666
Out of infinite choices,
that was the only one

425
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:58,000
that would prevent
wholesale destruction.

426
00:19:58,083 --> 00:20:00,166
And finding the one
river you needed,

427
00:20:00,250 --> 00:20:02,333
you and Mage
made it into reality.

428
00:20:02,416 --> 00:20:05,208
Derrida, never forget
how you feel right now.

429
00:20:05,291 --> 00:20:06,750
It’s not about what you do,

430
00:20:06,833 --> 00:20:08,916
it's about what you hope for.

431
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:11,708
Follow that path,
and the future will be waiting.

432
00:20:11,791 --> 00:20:12,583
[gasp]

433
00:20:12,666 --> 00:20:15,083
♪

434
00:20:17,083 --> 00:20:18,166
It’s you.

435
00:20:18,250 --> 00:20:20,208
Derrida. Shall we go?

436
00:20:20,291 --> 00:20:23,333
To the world where everything
is back where it belongs.

437
00:20:23,416 --> 00:20:24,625
[energy humming]

438
00:20:24,708 --> 00:20:26,708
[wind blowing]

439
00:20:28,791 --> 00:20:29,791
[bang]

440
00:20:33,041 --> 00:20:35,041
-[car approaching]
-[DERRIDA] Sorry!

441
00:20:35,125 --> 00:20:36,458
I know I’m late again.

442
00:20:36,541 --> 00:20:39,000
Well, you always are.

443
00:20:39,083 --> 00:20:40,833
[DERRIDA]
I gotta make it up to you.

444
00:20:40,916 --> 00:20:43,125
No need! It’s fine.

445
00:20:43,208 --> 00:20:44,916
I knew you’d come
get me eventually,

446
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:47,166
so all I had to do was wait.

447
00:20:47,250 --> 00:20:48,791
[giggle]

448
00:20:48,875 --> 00:20:50,458
[engine humming]

449
00:20:51,875 --> 00:20:54,041
♪

450
00:20:55,166 --> 00:20:58,333
[MAGE] The ripples in time have
changed a lot of things.

451
00:20:58,416 --> 00:21:00,916
But none of the people here,

452
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:03,416
existing in this present,
can remember it.

453
00:21:04,416 --> 00:21:06,875
So many possibilities.

454
00:21:06,958 --> 00:21:09,000
All the things that
could have happened.

455
00:21:09,083 --> 00:21:11,125
All the people they
could have met.

456
00:21:11,208 --> 00:21:14,708
[DERRIDA] This version of
the world avoided the war.

457
00:21:14,791 --> 00:21:16,583
That’s all that really matters.

458
00:21:18,208 --> 00:21:20,708
Have Joe and Spencer search
downtown for me, will ya?

459
00:21:20,791 --> 00:21:22,625
I’ll catch up soon.

460
00:21:24,416 --> 00:21:27,208
[MAN] I never really pictured
you as the “dad” kinda guy.

461
00:21:28,208 --> 00:21:30,083
Exciting, huh, “Papa?”

462
00:21:31,083 --> 00:21:32,083
[chuckle]

463
00:21:33,291 --> 00:21:35,958
[DERRIDA] What’s the key
to traveling through time?

464
00:21:36,041 --> 00:21:38,000
Huh? Baby!

465
00:21:38,083 --> 00:21:40,833
Yes, well, pretty soon, anyway!

466
00:21:40,916 --> 00:21:42,666
[MAYUKA]
Do you mind if I feel, miss?

467
00:21:42,750 --> 00:21:43,583
Go ahead.

468
00:21:44,666 --> 00:21:46,375
[DERRIDA] To memories
that can’t be erased.

469
00:21:46,458 --> 00:21:49,000
To special times and places.

470
00:21:49,083 --> 00:21:51,958
Why do humans long
to return to moments,

471
00:21:52,041 --> 00:21:54,958
they’ve randomly
designated as special?

472
00:21:55,041 --> 00:21:56,333
How cute!

473
00:21:56,416 --> 00:21:58,833
[MAYUKA]
That Automata has a ribbon on!

474
00:22:00,166 --> 00:22:01,541
Excuse me, what’s your name?

475
00:22:02,916 --> 00:22:04,541
[GRAHAM]
My name is Graham!

476
00:22:05,541 --> 00:22:07,791
[DERRIDA]
Traveling through time means

477
00:22:07,875 --> 00:22:09,916
tracing back through
your river of memories.

478
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:12,083
Caring about someone.

479
00:22:12,166 --> 00:22:14,875
Reflecting on yourself
once you’ve reached the end,

480
00:22:14,958 --> 00:22:16,000
the now.

481
00:22:16,083 --> 00:22:18,083
♪

482
00:22:20,250 --> 00:22:22,500
[JACQUES] How’s Derrida’s
research coming along?

483
00:22:22,583 --> 00:22:24,416
[NATHAN] I’m helping
him on my days off,

484
00:22:24,500 --> 00:22:26,250
but there’s not
a lot of progress.

485
00:22:26,333 --> 00:22:30,083
Traveling back in time is
still just an unrealized dream.

486
00:22:30,166 --> 00:22:31,166
Makes sense.

487
00:22:31,250 --> 00:22:32,625
It’s because it’s unrealized

488
00:22:32,708 --> 00:22:35,083
that people are still
pursuing that dream.

489
00:22:35,166 --> 00:22:36,083
[chuckle]

490
00:22:37,250 --> 00:22:38,083
[door opens]

491
00:22:39,583 --> 00:22:42,333
[MAGE] Sorry I’m late!
It was Derrida’s fault.

492
00:22:42,416 --> 00:22:43,875
[YURI]
Tardy again, huh?

493
00:22:43,958 --> 00:22:46,250
You really need to fix
that habit of yours.

494
00:22:46,333 --> 00:22:49,000
-[DERRIDA] Sorry.
-[YURI] Come on, get inside.

495
00:22:49,083 --> 00:22:50,500
-Wait, hold on!
-[BOTH] Huh?

496
00:22:50,583 --> 00:22:51,416
[shutter click]

497
00:22:52,875 --> 00:22:53,958
You two have fun!

498
00:22:56,916 --> 00:22:57,875
-[drip]
-[YURI] Huh?

499
00:22:57,958 --> 00:22:59,666
What the...?

500
00:22:59,750 --> 00:23:03,166
Why do I feel nostalgic looking
at a picture I just took?

501
00:23:04,166 --> 00:23:05,375
[MAN]
Miss Yuri Dietrich?

502
00:23:05,458 --> 00:23:06,625
Could I have
an interview, please?

503
00:23:06,708 --> 00:23:07,500
[gasp]

504
00:23:07,583 --> 00:23:08,583
♪

505
00:23:13,041 --> 00:23:14,916
[MAGE]
We’ll have to start over now.

506
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:17,333
A new life in a new world.

507
00:23:17,416 --> 00:23:19,541
But somehow, someway,

508
00:23:19,625 --> 00:23:21,791
I’m sure we’ll meet
them all again.

509
00:23:21,875 --> 00:23:24,166
Derrida? Think so?

510
00:23:24,250 --> 00:23:27,625
Of course. I know so.

511
00:23:27,708 --> 00:23:28,708
♪

512
00:23:30,750 --> 00:23:33,041
[DERRIDA] Because as long
as people have hope,

513
00:23:33,125 --> 00:23:35,250
the river will continue to flow,

514
00:23:35,333 --> 00:23:38,833
and the past and the future
will keep being born.

